45:52.984 --> 45:54.852 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It shows us 10 meters out.

45:54.952 --> 45:58.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Puckett is the
founder of
the Basel Action Network, a
Seattle-based

45:58.723 --> 46:02.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
watchdog group that investigates
the afterlife
of electronics.

46:02.360 --> 46:06.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: We are basically
trying to stop
the rich countries from dumping
their hazardous

46:06.497 --> 46:07.765 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
waste onto poor countries.

46:07.865 --> 46:10.234 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: In this case,
China.

46:10.334 --> 46:12.169 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: They're running.

46:12.269 --> 46:14.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: Running away?

46:14.805 --> 46:16.540 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:16.641 --> 46:21.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: To get inside, a
local driver
and translator posed as e-waste
buyers.

46:21.412 --> 46:30.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
Hello? We're here
to buy goods. We just want to
see the electronics.

46:30.988 --> 46:37.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: With people
buying new computers
and other electronics more
frequently than

46:37.928 --> 46:43.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ever, electronic waste is now
the fastest-growing
waste stream in the world. On
top of that,

46:43.534 --> 46:48.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it contains toxic materials that
can poison
people and the environment.

46:48.406 --> 46:53.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This investigation began months
ago, when
Puckett's team put GPS tracking
devices inside

46:53.511 --> 46:58.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
200 old computers, printers and
TVs. Then
they dropped them off at
locations across

46:58.449 --> 47:04.588 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the country at recycling
facilities, donation
centers and electronics
take-back programs,

47:04.689 --> 47:07.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including some of the industry's
most reputable
companies.

47:07.324 --> 47:11.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: We sat back and
said, where are
they going to go? And the little
devices went

47:12.063 --> 47:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
