this is where
I am.

47:15.166 --> 47:18.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Puckett's group
partnered
with Carlo Ratti of the
Senseable City Lab

47:18.502 --> 47:20.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology.

47:20.337 --> 47:23.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARLO RATTI, Senseable City Lab:
Tracking
is really the first step in
order to design

47:23.974 --> 47:29.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a better system. One of the
surprising things
we discovered is how far waste
travels. You

47:29.113 --> 47:33.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see this kind of global e-waste
flows that
actually almost cover the whole
planet.

47:33.484 --> 47:38.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Each device
traveled an average
of about 2,500 miles, and around
a third of

47:39.023 --> 47:45.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the tracked computers were
exported. Of those,
most ended up here. Hong Kong is
home to one

47:45.863 --> 47:51.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the world's busiest ports.
Ships deliver
more cargo than is possible to
inspect.

47:51.235 --> 47:55.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a result, Hong Kong has a
reputation for
being a transit point for
illegal trade and

47:55.773 --> 48:03.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
smuggling of all kinds. Most of
the exported
tracked devices led Puckett to a
little known

48:03.814 --> 48:05.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
part of Hong Kong called the New
Territories.

48:05.950 --> 48:09.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: It's really a
frontier. It's
really cowboy land out there.

48:09.787 --> 48:14.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Puckett followed
one tracked
printer here to a place that
calls itself

48:14.191 --> 48:14.992 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a farm.

48:15.092 --> 48:16.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Farmland.

48:16.427 --> 48:21.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: Farmland? Yes,
that's a great
farm in there.

48:21.132 --> 48:27.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You would have no idea that
there was a huge
scrap yard there until you look
over the fence.

48:28.072 --> 48:31.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Inside, they
found printers
being taken apart by immigrant
workers.

48:31.709 --> 48:36.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: I am looking for
asset tags to
tell me where the material came
from. I look

48:36.447 --> 48:40.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the environmental harm
issues. I look
for the workstations to see how
these workers

48:40.985 --> 48:42.720 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
might be exposed.

48:42.820 --> 48:47.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Many of the
workers handle
hazardous material without
protective gear.

48:47.158 --> 48:50.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One concern? Printer toner, a
probable carcinogen.

48:50.494 --> 48:55.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JIM PUCKETT: There is no
protections of this
labor force. There's no
occupational laws

48:55.266 --> 48:57.568 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that are going to protect them.

48:57.668 --> 49:01.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE CAMPBELL: Jackson Lau is
the head of
the Hong Kong Recycling
Association. He runs

49:01.939 --> 49:06.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a licensed recycling facility in
the New Territories.
And he says the junkyards in the
area that

49:06.710 --> 49:09.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
import e-waste are unlicensed
and unregulated.

49:09.346 --> 49:13.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKSON LAU, Hong Kong Recycling
Association
(through translator): These old
electronics

49:13.250 --> 49:17.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are usually being sorted and
dismantled, because
the leftover components are
worthless. They

49:18.088 --> 49:20.024 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
are being dumped
indiscriminately.

49:20.124 --> 49:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM PUCKETT: Look at the tubes,
many, many
tubes thrown on the ground here.

49:28.666 --> 49:33.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KATIE CAMPBELL: The white
fluorescent tubes
light up LCD screens. Each of
them contains

49:33.604 --> 49:35.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
